    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2297611691" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2297611691" />
    <a title="Michael Perkins" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13298726-michael-perkins"><img alt="Michael Perkins" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1454487234p2/13298726.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2297611691?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Perkins" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Perkins" href="/user/show/13298726-michael-perkins">Michael Perkins</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2297611691" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11515885872205014889">How other developed countries see the U.S healthcare system (short video)....<br/><br/><a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.nytimes.com/2021/04/28/opinion/healthcare-us.html?action=click&amp;module=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Homepage'>https://www.nytimes.com/2021/04/28/op...</a><br/><br/>=============================<br/><br/>“Doctors are men who prescribe medicines of which they know little, to cure diseases of which they know less, in human beings of whom they know nothing.”<br/><br/>This may seem harsh, but diagnosis is a lost art. Primary care doctors spend a mere 11 minutes per patient in an office visit, according to a new analysis. The history of the patient used to be seen as</span>
  <span id="freeText11515885872205014889" style="display:none">How other developed countries see the U.S healthcare system (short video)....<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/04/28/opinion/healthcare-us.html?action=click&amp;module=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Homepage">https://www.nytimes.com/2021/04/28/op...</a><br /><br />=============================<br /><br />“Doctors are men who prescribe medicines of which they know little, to cure diseases of which they know less, in human beings of whom they know nothing.”<br /><br />This may seem harsh, but diagnosis is a lost art. Primary care doctors spend a mere 11 minutes per patient in an office visit, according to a new analysis. The history of the patient used to be seen as essential in sorting out what's wrong. Instead it's a pill for every ill and insurance companies rewarding procedures over consults. Shotgun blast medicine that's the most expensive in the world.<br /><br />=========================<br /><br />Section IV on smoking and the extensive machinations of the Big Tobacco disinformation campaign is worth the price of the book alone. It's become a kind of playbook for other entities. I see some evidence of that in the gun lobby in the U.S. These entities have a lot of money that they put to use in influencing the people they want to. Although I am surprised that the author left out this later phase of the anti-smoking campaign <br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://profiles.nlm.nih.gov/spotlight/qq/feature/tobacco">https://profiles.nlm.nih.gov/spotligh...</a><br /><br />A note on style: This is not a dry textbook. The style is very fluid. Though rich in information, the narrative moves right along. Even the accounts of research read like engrossing detective stories.<br /><br />================</span>
  <a data-text-id="11515885872205014889" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


